<br>
There is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Yoyo Rooting,&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> but it is risky and inefficient in comparison to chaining pets.<br>
<br>
How am I mistaken? I have read nothing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(and I moderate the mage forums, and so am fairly well read)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to suggest that buffing and sustaining a pet works against experience yielding mobs from 61st to 63rd level. While individual opponents might be found that can be defeated in that manner, I doubt that the sustained experience gain is even half of what can be had by chaining pets, experience gain being generally the point of soloing.<br>
<br>
As for the role of the pet, I would be satisfied with a sustained DPS pet, as all our other pets are, but with the added utility that it deals that damage as a caster, at a distance. It is not required to do more damage than a water pet, and I cannot recall anyone other than you suggesting that it should. If it outdamaged the water pet while not requiring positioning, it would be almost always be better than the water pet. But then, only you suggested that.<br>
<br>
If it dealt damage comparable to air, maybe a little higher, cast stuns, tanked worse than water, dealt less damage than water but did not require positioning, then you would have a useful caster-type fire pet, with unique attributes.<br>
<br>
As regards a &quot;burst DPS&quot; pet, I am undecided. But is again only natural that mages consider the possibility now that it has been brought up. Is a burst DPS pet useful? Appropriate? Overpowering? I don't know, but I do know that discussing that is worthwhile.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
